title: For Sale:  Beretta PX4 Storm Subcompact .40
postcontent:
Don't settle for those little .380 pocket guns for your conceal carry firepower. Use something proper, small, sexy, safe, and reliable. Ok, marketting talk is over.

This was for my wife who I thought would like it for it's DA/SA, decocker, and safety. She now prefers a striker fired gun without safeties or SA (and I'm sure it'll take another gun or two before she decides). We've put about a box or two through it (less than 100 rounds) without issues. I've had other Berettas and their quality, customer service (if needed), fit and finish and reliability is outstanding...this PX4 SC is no exception. It's light weight, very easy to control and get off quick follow up shots. The DA trigger pull is a smooth and crisp 7lbs giving some peace of mind when carrying. The SA pull is probably about 4lbs, maybe a pinch less. The decocker is a nice bonus. Included is a never worn factory Beretta pancake holster made for and embossed with the PX4 Storm logo on it...still needs breaking in.

I paid $500 for the gun and another $50 for the holster. I'm asking $475 for it all and I'll throw in 50 hydrashok (180grain) rounds and ONE full mag of my good stuff (180 grain black talons). There's no real wear, scuffs, or marks (not even smileys on the barrel). This gun is "as new" as you can get shy of being NIB.

More details/specs here: 
http://www.berettausa.com/products/px4-storm-type-f-sub-compact/

Private party transaction (face to face) only, I'll drive no further north than Missoula and no further south than Darby in the Bitterroot Valley. If you're not legally able to buy/possess a gun don't waste your time contacting me.

title: For Sale:  Stoeger Cougar 8000, 9mm
postcontent:
Before you think this is a ‘step-down’ from a ‘True’ Beretta, here is a little background:

Stoeger Industries is a subsidiary of Beretta. The Stoeger Cougars are made in Turkey using the same machinery that Beretta used to make the original Cougars. It is every bit the quality of the Beretta. The Stoeger 8000 in 9mm is identical to the Beretta Cougar L Type P (Cougar L slide, lighter barrel and beveled slide, but with a full-length magazine).
It’s an ergonomically advanced pistol, compact but capable of handling high-power cartridges as the 9 mm Parabellum, with great fire capacity and extraordinary long life.  This has been possible also thanks to a brilliant adaptation of a proven locked breech system with a Unique Rotating Barrel.  By channeling part of the recoil energy into barrel rotation, and by partially absorbing the barrel and slide recoil shock through the central block before it is transferred to the frame, the cougar achieves unusually low felt recoil.

title: For Trade:  Wicked Lasers Spyder Arctic III 1 Watt blue laser. Burns/Cuts/Melts
postcontent:
This is a brand new Wicked Lasers Spyder III Arctic 1 watt blue laser. Right off the bat, I'll tell you that you can go on to Wicked Laser's website right now and order this very laser for $299.99. However, I won't take anything close to that. The FDA (yes FDA) has put an import ban on any handheld laser above 5mw. This particular laser is 200x more powerful then what current import allows. Actually getting your hands on one of these is VERY diffcult. I'm a GM for UPS and even with my connections in customs, it still took me 6 1/2 months to get a hold of mine. From what I'm told 85% of these are seized.

  However, once you DO have one, they are pretty incredible. It will burn or melt most things dark colored. You can cut through plastics, light cigs, pop ballons, start fires, etc. The beam is so powerful that if you pointed it straight up in the air, no only can you see the beam the entire way up, but the only reason it doesn't hit outter space is because our inner atmosphere diffuses the beam. If you were at sea, and pointed the beam straight out infront of you, the only reason you aren't able to see it past a certain point is because of the curvature of the Earth.



I understand this isn't what you typically see, so if you have any questions feel free to ask.
